<div class="body" id="fhbody-175451091">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-175451091" class="p">
			
		 	
				Google will require all new mobile chipsets launching with Android 15 to <a href="https://www.androidauthority.com/android-15-virtual-machine-mandate-3498428/">support its Android Virtualization Framework</a> (AVF), a significant shift in the operating system's security architecture. The mandate, reports AndroidAuthority that got a hold of Android's latest Vendor Software Requirements document, affects major chipmakers including Qualcomm, MediaTek, and Samsung's Exynos division. New processors like the Snapdragon 8 Elite and Dimensity 9400 must implement AVF support to receive Android certification. <br> <br>

AVF, introduced with Android 13, creates isolated environments for security-sensitive operations including code compilation and DRM applications. The framework also enables full operating system virtualization, with Google demonstrating Chrome OS running in a virtual machine on Android devices.<br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
	</div>
