	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64938499"><p><div class="quote"><p>AFAICS they simply assume that during the early parts of booting the Android kernel is secure, it loads the the KVM low-visor into EL2 and after that it can't mess with it any more even if it gets compromised down the line.</p></div><p>That makes perfect sense and is a lot simpler than I though.  Thanks!

</p><p>And, yes, the assumption is definitely that the system is secure until the "low-visor" (I like that term) has been loaded into EL2. If the attacker can compromise anything before that, the game is over. Which does make the VMs potentially less secure than TrustZone apps, because the TCB is much larger.  And I expect the really critical security stuff will actually stay in TZ, where it will benefit from moving all the rest out of TZ.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64938499">

